A Bloblang mapping defines a transformation that can be applied to messages. Mappings can be added as part of a pipeline with the xref:components:processors/bloblang.adoc[`bloblang` processor] or used directly within many component configurations as an xref:guides:bloblang/about.adoc#interpolation[interpolation] expression.

To run a mapping interactively, try the https://play.benthos.dev[Bloblang playground,window=_blank].

== Assignment

The left-hand side of a Bloblang statement is always a xref:guides:bloblang/about.adoc#paths[path] within the output document.

For example, the following Bloblang mapping creates a new document where the field `foo.bar` is set to a string `"hello world"`:

```coffee
root.foo.bar = "hello world"
```

The keyword `root` refers to the root of the output document. When a mapping executes it starts with an empty `root`, which is populated as the mapping runs.

The keyword `this` refers to the root of the input (source) document. As you descend into nested fields via `this`, it is contextually updated to point to the current level in the input.

The following example swaps the values of `foo` and `bar`:

```coffee
root.foo = this.bar
root.bar = this.foo
```

=== Paths

A path in a Bloblang mapping is any sequence of period-delimited identifiers or array indexes (integers). For example, a simple string field `"foo"`:

```coffee
root.foo = this.bar.baz
```

Array access with numeric index:

```coffee
root.first_element = this.some_array.0
```

=== Special Characters in Paths

If a field identifier contains a period (`.`) or any other special character then it's possible to quote the identifier in the path:

```coffee
root."foo.bar".baz = this.thing
```

=== Non-Structured Data

If your input is a byte array or a scalar value rather than a structured object it can be referred to by using the `root` keyword on the right-hand side of a mapping:

```coffee
root = root.uppercase()
```

== Deleting

It is possible to selectively delete fields from a document using the `deleted()` function:

```coffee
root = this
root.unwanted_field = deleted()
root.another_unwanted_field = deleted()
```

== Variables

Bloblang supports variables using `let`, followed by a name beginning with `$`. Variables can be used anywhere within a mapping but are not included in the output:

```coffee
let foo = "the foo value"
root.bar = $foo
```

== Metadata

Redpanda Connect message metadata can be accessed and modified using the `meta` keyword:

```coffee
root.foo = meta("kafka_topic")
meta("output_topic") = this.some_field
```

== Coalesce

The pipe `|` operator can be used on the right-hand side of a statement to coalesce multiple values together, for example:

```coffee
root.foo = this.foo | this.bar | "default value"
```

This can also be used on fields within a JSON array:

```coffee
root.urls = this.urls.map_each(this.url | this.address)
```

== Literals

Bloblang supports number, boolean, string, null, array, and object literals.

=== Numbers

Numbers are either integers (stored as 64-bit signed integers) or floats (stored as 64-bit floating-point). Negative numbers use a leading `-`. A leading `+` is not supported.

```coffee
root.an_integer = 42
root.negative   = -7
root.a_float    = 3.14
root.scientific = 1.0e3
```

=== Booleans

Boolean values are the lowercase words `true` and `false`:

```coffee
root.is_enabled = true
root.is_disabled = false
```

=== Null

The null value is the lowercase word `null`:

```coffee
root.optional_field = null
```

=== Strings

Strings are enclosed in double quotes. The following escape sequences are supported:

[cols="1,3"]
|===
| Sequence | Meaning

| `\\`
| Literal backslash

| `\"`
| Double quote

| `\n`
| Newline (LF)

| `\r`
| Carriage return (CR)

| `\t`
| Horizontal tab

| `\b`
| Backspace

| `\f`
| Form feed

| `\uXXXX`
| Unicode code point (4 hex digits)

| `\UXXXXXXXX`
| Unicode code point (8 hex digits)
|===

Literal (unescaped) newlines are not permitted inside a double-quoted string. Use `\n` or triple-quoted strings for multiline content.

```coffee
root.greeting = "Hello, \"world\"!\nSecond line."
root.tab_sep  = "column1\tcolumn2"
root.unicode  = "\u00e9l\u00e8ve"
```

==== Triple-Quoted Strings

Strings can also be enclosed in triple double-quotes (`"""`). Inside a triple-quoted string:

* Backslashes are treated as literal characters — no escape processing is performed.
* Newlines are preserved exactly as written.
* Single and double quote characters (`"`, `""`) are literal and do not need escaping.
* The only sequence that cannot appear inside the string is three consecutive double-quotes (`"""`), which terminates the string.

Triple-quoted strings are useful for SQL queries, JSON templates, regex patterns, and any other content where backslash escaping would make the text harder to read:

```coffee
# Regular string — backslashes must be doubled
root.pattern_a = "^\\d{3}-\\d{4}$"

# Triple-quoted string — backslashes are literal
root.pattern_b = """^\d{3}-\d{4}$"""
```

A multi-line SQL query:

```coffee
root.query = """SELECT *
FROM orders
WHERE status = 'pending'
  AND created_at > now() - INTERVAL '1 day'"""
```

A JSON template with embedded quotes:

```coffee
root.tmpl = """{"type": "notification", "msg": "hello"}"""
```

Because no escape processing occurs, the following two assignments produce the same result:

```coffee
root.a = """C:\Users\data"""
root.b = "C:\\Users\\data"
```

=== Arrays

Arrays use square brackets with comma-separated values. Values can be any literal or dynamic expression:

```coffee
root.tags = ["foo", "bar", "baz"]
root.mixed = [42, true, "hello", null]
```

=== Objects

Objects use curly braces with colon-separated key-value pairs:

```coffee
root.meta = {"source": "kafka", "version": 2}
```

=== Dynamic Expressions

The values within literal arrays and objects can be dynamic query expressions, as well as the keys of object literals:

```coffee
root.a = [this.foo, this.bar]
root.b = {"accnt": this.account}
```

== Comments

Use `#` to add comments in Bloblang:

```coffee
# Here's a comment
root.id = this.thing # And a trailing comment
```

== Boolean Logic

Bloblang supports a standard set of boolean operators `&&`, `||`, `!`, and comparison operators `==`, `!=`, `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`:

```coffee
root.is_foo = (this.thing == "foo" && this.other != "bar")
```

== Arithmetic

Bloblang supports basic arithmetic operators `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`:

```coffee
root.result = (this.foo * 7) + (this.bar / 2)
```

== Conditional Mapping

Use `if` and `else` for conditional mapping:

```coffee
root.foo = if this.bar == "something" {
  this.baz
} else if this.bar == "otherthing" {
  this.qux
} else {
  "default"
}
```

== Pattern Matching

Use `match` to match against an expression:

```coffee
root.new_doc = match this.doc {
  this.type == "article" => this.article
  this.type == "comment" => this.comment
  _ => this
}
```

Or without an expression, match against `true`:

```coffee
root.new_doc = match {
  this.doc.type == "article" => this.doc.article
  this.doc.type == "comment" => this.doc.comment
  _ => this.doc
}
```

== Functions

Use xref:guides:bloblang/functions.adoc[Bloblang functions] to obtain values from the environment:

```coffee
root.id = uuid_v4()
```

== Methods

Use xref:guides:bloblang/methods.adoc[Bloblang methods] to apply transformations to existing values:

```coffee
root.foo = this.foo.trim().uppercase()
```

== Maps

It's possible to declare reusable maps within your mapping:

```coffee
map formatting {
  root.foo = this.foo.uppercase()
  root.bar = this.bar.trim()
}

root.apply_to = this.some_object.apply("formatting")
```

=== Importing Maps

It's also possible to import maps defined in other files:

```coffee
import "./formatters.blobl"

root = this.apply("my_formatter")
```

== Filtering

Bloblang can be used as a filter by assigning `root` to `deleted()`:

```coffee
root = if this.type != "foo" {
  deleted()
}
```

== Error Handling

Functions and methods can fail under certain circumstances, such as when they receive arguments of the wrong type. These failures, when uncaught, will cause the entire mapping to fail. When a failure occurs within a coalesce expression the next expression in the chain is executed instead. For example:

```coffee
root.foo = this.thing.number() | 0
```

The default value of `0` will be assigned when `thing.number()` fails. However, if the field `thing` doesn't exist at all an error will still be thrown. To suppress errors on a field level simply use `catch`:

```coffee
root.foo = this.thing.catch(null)
```

It's also possible to define a mapping that catches errors on the document level and instead assigns a modified message to the root:

```coffee
map catch_all {
  root = this
  root.err = error()
}

root = this.apply("catch_all").catch(this)
```

Or simply assign a fallback value to `root`:

```coffee
root = this.catch(this)
```

A message that is not modified by the mapping (`root` is unchanged from its default empty value) is dropped unless it is otherwise modified by a subsequent mapping or xref:components:processors/bloblang.adoc[component]. If a message is dropped it will not be sent anywhere.

If the `or` method is used on the right-hand side without a coalesce chain, it's used for providing default or fallback values:

```coffee
root.foo = this.foo.or("default")
```
